Blind Americans Equality Day, which falls on October 15th, marks the 100th anniversary of the Federal Vocational Rehabilitation (VR) program. This program empowers individuals with disabilities, including those who are blind or visually impaired, to pursue competitive employment opportunities. The article also mentions the 45th anniversary of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act and the 30th anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act, both of which have played a significant role in protecting the rights of individuals with disabilities. The Trump Administration expresses support for programs that combat the stigmas faced by blind and visually impaired individuals in finding employment. The article also highlights the success of small businesses operating under the Randolph-Sheppard Act of 1936, which facilitates the entrepreneurial aspirations of the blind and visually impaired. President Donald J. Trump proclaims October 15, 2020, as Blind Americans Equality Day and calls upon all Americans to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities to reaffirm the commitment to achieving equality for all Americans.